## Background

The Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory (LIGO) consists of two observingsites separated by 3 000 km. On 14 September 2015 both observing sites detected a transient gravitational-wave signal separated in time by less than the light-travel time between the two observing sites. The detected signals lasted less than 0.2 seconds and had a upward chirp in frequency. The signals were consistent with that predicted Einstein’s theory of general relativity
for the in-spiral and merger of two black holes (B.P. Abbott et al., *Observation of Gravitational Waves from a Binary Black Hole Merger*, Phys. Rev. Lett., 2016, **116**, 061102). Further details of the LIGO project can be found at **http://www.ligo.org/**.

## The Project

In this project you will use *simulated* data in the style of LIGO. The data are continuously  sampled at a rate of 4096 Hz for a duration of 32 seconds. The two sites ‘A’ and ‘B’, separated by 3 000 km, both have a chirp-like signal, also of cosmological origin, similar to that found by the real LIGO. These are “buried” in the signals instrumental and environmental noise sources. Some of the noise sources are strictly periodic; others are not.

The necessary data file can be downloaded from the *Project* folder of the module pages on the *KLE*. The simulated data file is of the form **username.dat**, where **username** is your *KLE* username. The data set is unique to you. The file contains three columns; time of measurement in seconds, data for Site ‘A’ and ‘B’ in arbitrary units. Both sites have their time synchronised to a precision better than the sampling rate.

Use python to analyse these data, in order to determine at least the following:
* Identify and characterise the noise sources in the data from the two sites.
* Perform procedures to mitigate against the sources of noise.
* Identify and isolate the chirp signal in the data from both sites.
* Determine the time separation between the chirp signals recorded by the two sites.

Details of your analysis and the results found are to be presented in a report.

## Introduction

![alt-text](https://i.imgur.com/a8mTHd7.jpg "LIGO Observatory Locations")

On September 14, 2015, the just-built Advanced LIGO (Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory) detectors made the world's first direct detection of gravitational waves. Two merging and colliding black holes, **1.3 billion light years away**, were the source of these gravitational waves<sup>[<a href=#ref1>1</a>]</sup>. 


The two LIGO observatories that detected the waves first are in Hanford, USA and with the other being in Livingston, USA. The map above illustrates this further. At both sites, there is a laser interferometer consisting of two 4km long arms. These arms are capable of detecting a change of 1/10,000th of a width of a proton between its mirrors<sup>[<a href=#ref2>2</a>]</sup>. This allows for the minute changes in length caused by passing gravitational waves. Normally, if the two arms are exactly 4km equidistant, the resulting wave that arrives at the photodetector will have zero intensity. This is because the two waves cancel each other. However, when passing gravitational waves interact with the lasers within the arms, it causes nonequidistant lengths. This means that some intensity of light can be detected by the photodetector. The animation below demonstrates this.

![alt text](https://i.imgur.com/WrZOuhO.gif "Gravitational Waves Passing LIGO [3]")
Video <sup>[<a href=#ref3>3</a>]</sup>

This project aims to detect a simulated gravitation chirp buried into a very strongly 'coloured' signal from two sites, like the real world Livingston and Hanford.

The above plot of the Fourier transforms of the waveforms highlights the periodic noise the data hosts. We will be wanting to whiten the data to remove this cyclic noise.

The graph above has been cut in half as we only want the positive sample frequencies. In the Scipy documentation the output array goes as follows:

```Python
f = [0, 1, ...,   n/2-1,     -n/2, ..., -1] / (d*n)   if n is even
f = [0, 1, ..., (n-1)/2, -(n-1)/2, ..., -1] / (d*n)   if n is odd
```

As n is even in this case, to get all positive values, 0 to the length of the array divided by two works.

```python
def pre_whiten(userInput, y, t, dt):
    
    func = lambda t, freq, phase, amp, offset: amp * np.sin(t * 2 * np.pi * freq + phase) + offset
    
    for i in range(userInput):
        ft = np.abs(fftpack.rfft(y)) / len(y) * 2  # amplitude rather than power
        freqs = fftpack.rfftfreq(len(t), d=dt)

        freq_est = freqs[np.argmax(ft)]  # frequency of highest peak in FFT
        amp_est = np.max(ft)  # amplitude of the highest peak in FFT

        matrixA = np.vstack(
            [
                np.sin(freq_est * 2 * np.pi * t),
                np.cos(freq_est * 2 * np.pi * t),
                np.ones(len(t))
            ]).T
        alpha = np.dot(matrixA.T, matrixA)
        beta = np.dot(matrixA.T, y)

        matrixC = np.linalg.inv(alpha)  # covariance matrix
        afit = np.dot(matrixC, beta)  # solution vector
        phase_est = atan2(afit[1], afit[0])

        # Assume offset is zero
        popt, pcov = curve_fit(func, t, y, p0=[freq_est, phase_est, amp_est, 0])

        y2 = y - func(t, *popt)  # subtract fit from data
        y = y2
    return y
```

The above function removes the most prominent periodic noise from our data. ***userInput*** is the number of times that the function will run for. 40 times has been chosen, as the function is quite computationally  heavy and it seems that running it more than 30 times has no effect on the output. Whilst 40 possibly unnecessary as just mentioned, it makes sure that all unwanted noise is eliminated. 


```python
white_a = pre_whiten(40, site_a, time, dt)
white_b = pre_whiten(40, site_b, time, dt)
```

We can see that the whitened spectrogram has almost been removed of all periodic noise. More importantly, we now see an exponential or polynomial type smudge - our signal! It is 'chirping' from a lower to a higher frequency, within a 0.2-second time frame. This is far-reaching, as we can apply a band-pass to a more accurate range of critical frequencies. A band-pass filter will remove frequencies above and below critical points. Both of these curves seem to peak at around 600Hz.

The above graph has been zoomed in to around the site of the chirp of both site A and B, based off the spectrograph. It seems like the chirp is located between 19 and 20 seconds. However, there is obviously noise that must be got rid of, before we can properly see the chirp.

We could apply a Gaussian filter to our data to filter out the upper and lower frequencies with the following code:

```Python
f_low = 700
f_high = 70

high_gauss_curve_a = 1 - np.exp(-(0.5 * white_freqs_a  / f_high) ** 2)
high_gauss_curve_b = 1 - np.exp(-(0.5 * white_freqs_b  / f_high) ** 2)

low_gauss_curve_a = np.exp(-(0.5 * white_freqs_a  / f_low) ** 2)
low_gauss_curve_b = np.exp(-(0.5 * white_freqs_b  / f_low) ** 2)

ft_filtered_a = high_gauss_curve_a * low_gauss_curve_a * white_ft_a
ft_filtered_b = high_gauss_curve_b * low_gauss_curve_b * white_ft_b

filtered_a = fftpack.ifft(ft_filtered_a).real
filtered_b = fftpack.ifft(ft_filtered_b).real
```

However, as we now accurately know the location of the critical band of frequencies  that our chirp is within, we can apply a more aggressive filter. A Butterworth filter will be able to more aggressively achieve this as it is designed to have a frequency response as flat as possible in the passband.


```python
bb, ab = butter(6, [50/fs, 650/fs], btype='band')  # critical freqs at 50 and 650
site_a_whitebp = filtfilt(bb, ab, white_a)
site_b_whitebp = filtfilt(bb, ab, white_b)
ft_site_a_whitebp = fftpack.ifft(site_a_whitebp).real
ft_site_b_whitebp = fftpack.ifft(site_b_whitebp).real
```

The input of 6 in the ***butter*** function is the order of the filter. The higher this value, the more aggressively or sharply the signal will be filtered. We want a somewhat large value, as we know approximately  the region of our chirp. The critical values of 50 and 650 have been chosen, as they are just outside the region in which this filter will start to clip the chirp.

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="1604">


The delay in two signals can be mathematically represented by:
$$\tau_{delay}=\overset{\mbox{arg max}}{t\in\mathbb{R}}(f\star g)(t)$$
That is to say, the time delay is equal to the maximum value of the cross correlation between the two functions. This gif is a helpful animation, showing how correlation is calculated at each point.

<a id="page-ref4"></a>
![alt-text](https://i.imgur.com/zPNougi.gif "Cross Correlation Animation")
Video<sup>[<a href="#ref4">4</a>]</sup>
***


You can see with the animation above that the maximum correlation happens when the two waves align perfectly. This is how the graph above has been produced. In our case, the two signals are the same, with differing noise and delay. This means that there should be a spike in correlation when the two signals almost perfectly align. We indeed see that this is the case in the graph above, this spike occurs at 0.063 seconds.

<a id="page-ref5"></a>
This value makes sense, as with the distance (3002 *km*) the chord makes between Hanford and Livingston, takes light $\tau=\frac{3002\cdot1000}{2.998\cdot10^{8}}=0.01$ secs to travel. The actual time delay found with the first detection of gravitational waves as found to be 7ms<sup>[<a href="#ref5">5</a>]</sup>. This shows that the delay calculated here is reasonable.

map = Basemap(projection='ortho', lon_0=lon_0, lat_0=lat_0, resolution='f')

# Map details
map.drawmapboundary(fill_color='#A6CAE0', linewidth=0)
map.fillcontinents(color='grey', alpha=0.3)
map.drawcoastlines(linewidth=0.1, color="white")
map.drawrivers(linewidth=0.1, color="white")
map.drawstates(linewidth=0.1, color="black")
map.drawcountries(linewidth=0.3, color="black")

# Calc. coodinate location for projection
x, y = map(lons, lats)

# Add a point per position
map.scatter(x, y)

# Calc. coodinate location for projection
xpt1, ypt1 = map(lons[0], lats[0])
xpt2, ypt2 = map(lons[1], lats[1])

# Calc. North and West location from projection
lonpt1, latpt1 = map(xpt1, ypt1, inverse=True)
lonpt2, latpt2 = map(xpt2, ypt2, inverse=True)

# Print text onto map, + 50000 to offset
plt.text(
    xpt1 + 50000, ypt1 + 50000,
    f'LIGO Hanford Observatory ({np.round(lonpt1, 2)}W, {np.round(latpt1)}N)'
)
plt.text(
    xpt2 + 50000, ypt2 + 50000,
    f'LIGO Livingston Observatory ({np.round(lonpt2, 2)}W, {np.round(latpt2, 2)}N)'
)

# Draw line between labs
map.drawgreatcircle(lons[0], lats[0], lons[1], lats[1], linewidth=2, color='orange')

# Haversine formula, converts lons and lats to distance
lon1 = np.deg2rad(lons[0])
lon2 = np.deg2rad(lons[1])
lat1 = np.deg2rad(lats[0])
lat2 = np.deg2rad(lats[1])

dlon = lon2 - lon1
dlat = lat2 - lat1
a = np.sin(dlat / 2) ** 2 + np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin(dlon / 2) ** 2
c = 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))
km = int(np.round(6371 * c, 0))

xpt3, ypt3 = map(lon_0, lat_0)

plt.text(xpt3 + 200000, ypt3 + 200000, f'{km} km')

plt.show()
